<TEXT>
a northwest airlines dc10 made an emergency 
landing wednesday after the trimotor jets no 2 engine apparently 
began breaking up and the pilot shut it down officials said 
flight 308 carrying 256 people from los angeles to minneapolis 
landed without incident at stapleton international airport 
wednesday about 630 pm according to richard boulware a 
spokesman at the airport 
they experienced a severe vibration from the no 2 engine 
and as a precautionary measure they elected to make an 
unscheduled landing said kevin whalen a spokesman for the st 
paul minnbased airline 
the no 2 engine of a dc10 also is the focus of an 
investigation into the crash of united airlines flight 232 last 
month in sioux city iowa killing 111 of the nearly 300 people 
aboard 
flight 232s no 2 engine apparently disintegrated shooting 
shrapnel that apparently severed hydraulic lines in the jet 
causing almost complete loss of control and forcing the 
crashlanding at sioux citys airport 
the investigation into the cause of that disaster is continuing 
boulware who observed the damage to the aircraft after it 
landed wednesday night said there were multiple shrapnellike 
holes in the outer cowling of the no 2 engine which on a dc10 
is mounted in the vertical stabilizer at the tail of the aircraft 
the other two engines are mounted under the wings 
one of the holes was big enough i could have stuck by hand 
through he said he said the holes were along the upper side of 
the engine cowling whatever exited exited upward he said 
he also said a service door on the tail about eight inches 
square had been blown open but remained attached to its hinges 
whalen said the landing was normal in terms of controlling the 
airplane and the 245 passengers were being placed on alternate 
flights to minneapolis there were 11 crew members on board he 
said 
whalen said the airlines mechanics will take a close look at 
the engine and since northwest doesnt have a maintenance base in 
denver the jet might have to be shuttled to minneapolis 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

