<TEXT>
six newspapers have been selected as finalists 
in the annual freedom of information award competition sponsored by 
the associated press managing editors association 
the finalists were announced tuesday by david hawpe of the 
courierjournal of louisville ky chairman of the apme freedom of 
information committee 
they are 
the daily southtown economist of chicago for successful 
efforts to force release of presentencing letters and reports that 
a judge said influenced him in sentencing the willow springs ill 
police chief 
the detroit news for successful efforts to document a city 
redevelopment project that cost the taxpayers 40 million 
the richmond va timesdispatch for successful efforts to 
open juvenile records in the case of the late rakie cloyd 
the san jose calif mercury news for efforts to open 
legislators driving records and for revealing secret meetings of 
the state legislature 
the spokesmanreview and spokane chronicle of spokane wash 
for efforts to obtain records illustrating the problem of sexual 
abuse of students by teachers 
the washington post for an examination of the way in which 
corporations and institutions use court secrecy to prevent 
disclosure of critical information relating to health and safety 
issues 
the winning entry will be announced at the apme convention in 
october in des moines iowa 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890809-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after a twomonth false start japans governing 
party is on another clean start to reform itself 
the false start was under sousuke uno who became prime minister 
june 2 with pledges of political reform but soon was pursued by 
allegations of having kept paid mistresses 
now another veteran legislator with no personal power base has 
been pulled up to lead the liberal democratic party 
there was an eerie sense of deja vu in toshiki kaifus 
acceptance remarks if he had unos glasses and streak of white 
hair it would have been hard to discern that japan had a new 
leader 
uno was clear of involvement in the recruit influencebuying 
scandal that caused his predecessor noboru takeshita to leave 
office prematurely 
kaifu bears the minor taint of receiving the equivalent of 
110000 in donations from recruit co over five years but he did 
not receive profits from cutprice stock deals as did most of the 
party leaders now sidelined 
that scandal uno said on june 2 has had a dramatic effect on 
our party i would like to take this opportunity to reflect on this 
development so we can make a clean start in politics and regain the 
confidence of our people 
kaifu said tuesday after winning the party presidency that it 
was a crucial time he called for debate through which we can 
gain the peoples understanding of our policies 
i want to carry out reforms and pass reform legislation based 
on our deep selfreflection he said we must carry out 
political reforms and shed our old skin 
like uno and takeshita and almost everyone else in his 
conservative party kaifu said the liberal democrats were in a 
crisis 
the crisis appears deeper than ever and the calendar is moving 
steadily toward the next encounter with the electorate 
in elections july 23 the liberal democrats lost constrol of 
parliaments upper house for the first time in the partys 34year 
history 
elections for all seats in the lower house must be called by 
july 1990 but the socialistled opposition in the upper chamber 
will try to create a legislative deadlock to make the government 
hold them sooner 
so low is the liberal democrats popularity that analysts expect 
they would lose their majority in the lower house 
the reasons are many and not easy to overcome 
despite a pledge not to impose a new major tax the governing 
party bulldozed a 3 percent sales tax through parliament 
when it was coupled with reductions in personal income and 
inheritance taxes the net effect was a reduction in the average 
households tax burden but the sales tax remains unpopular it 
also produces 10 percent of government revenue which makes 
abolishing it expensive 
although the recruit scandal ended officially in april with the 
indictment of two legislators on bribetaking charges it lives on 
in the minds of many who feel party leaders should not have escaped 
prosecution among those who did was yasuhiro nakasone who 
preceded takeshita as prime minister 
the easy money politicians reaped from the recruit co was 
spread so widely that nearly all top liberal democratic figures 
were tainted making it impossible for them to succeed takeshita or 
uno they remain powerful however and voters know many hope for 
future high office 
to the sales tax and recruit scandal which created an image of 
arrogance and unaccountability was added the insult to women of 
unos alleged affairs the result was the thrashing the liberal 
democrats took in the july 23 election 
takako doi the first woman to lead a party in japan is popular 
and has been able to fuzz over her socialist partys policy of an 
unarmed neutral japan which is not the majority opinion she 
attacks the sales tax and the governing partys image 
kaifu is new and untried he is 58 still boyishlooking young 
enough in japanese politics to suggest a new generation and has 
reform credentials from service under takeo miki a mr clean 
prime minister of the 1970s 
he has until october when the party votes again on its 
president to show he has made a good start on rescuing the deeply 
troubled party 
if he doesnt japan could be looking for its fourth prime 
minister of 1989 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
larry thorson is asia news editor of the 
associated press 
</TEXT>
