<TEXT>
though many people have a strong aversion to 
maggots the parents of a 17yearold girl say the centuriesold 
practice of allowing the fly larvae to eat decaying human tissue 
may have saved their daughters legs 
my husband said lets go for it and shannon said lets go 
for it so we did and it worked patsy dillingham the patients 
mother said tuesday 
shannon dillingham became critically ill suddenly on may 10 and 
was taken from a clinic to childrens hospital in washington the 
next day 
doctors there diagnosed her illness as meningococcemia a 
bloodborne bacterial infection that caused heart failure kidney 
problems and diseased skin and eventually led to the amputation of 
part of one leg and the toes on the other foot 
dr alan fields of the hospital staff said antibiotics used to 
kill the bacteria released a powerful toxin in dillinghams 
circulatory system that caused blood clots reducing the flow of 
blood to her legs 
meanwhile the bacteria continued its direct attack on her skin 
rotting it from the inside out said her father thomas dillingham 
a poolesville town commissioner 
once shannons doctors amputated her left leg below the knee and 
her toes on the right foot they still were faced with cleaning the 
remaining skin so skin grafts could be done antibiotics did not 
work fast enough and paring the skin from her legs did not work 
well enough her doctors said 
with shannons tissue dying they needed to do something 
said patsy dillingham when they use surgery they take the live 
tissue as well as the dead tissue and they had taken so much that 
they wanted to avoid that at all cost all of her skin from the 
waist down was dying 
after a long search by the hospital and the dillinghams more 
than 1500 fly larvae were located in ohio on july 21 shannon 
watched as the insects so tiny she could barely seem them were 
released onto her legs and secured with tape 
at first they tickled when they put them in my nurse and i 
were laughing she said i could feel them moving everywhere 
after 36 hours doctors used a highpressure hose to wash them 
away by then the maggots had grown from less than onesixteenth 
inch in diameter to nearly as big around as the end of a little 
finger her father said 
its a gruesome issue but we know that it can work said 
dr thomas t provost chairman of the department of dermatology at 
johns hopkins hospital its clinically wellknown that maggots 
will eat the dead tissue while leaving healthy tissue intact 
maggots have been used for centuries to remove dead tissue from 
infected wounds said dr joel howell assistant professor of 
internal medicine and history at the university of michigan medical 
center in ann arbor 
when you have an infected wound youd rather have an animal 
like a maggot eat it up rather than letting the infectious 
tissue stay there howell said it was probably used more 
before antibiotics or when it was more difficult for people to get 
to surgery 
although the treatment has been used in the united states since 
at least the civil war provost said it has been used in modern 
times only as a last resort because of peoples aversion to the 
maggots 
it is really horrendous provost said and most physicians 
are reluctant to do it because it tends to be sensationalized 
but dillingham a former teacher of biology physiology and 
anatomy was familiar with the cleaning capabilities of the insects 
and encouraged his daughter to try it 
i just wanted to get out of the hospital said shannon who 
is senior class president and a member of the poolsville 
juniorsenior high school track team if the maggots meant i 
could get out sooner then i wanted them to use them 
shannons doctors are optimistic she will walk again with 
protheses 
the grafts have taken a hundred percent her mother said 
were on the home stretch now 
