<DOCNO> AP890809-0145 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are some of the highlights of the savings 
and loan industry bailout legislation signed into law by president 
bush on wednesday 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the bailout will cost an estimated 159 billion through 1999 
including 605 billion to meet government obligations incurred in 
the rescue of 223 sampls in 1988 742 billion to close or merge 
more than 500 more sampls and 244 billion for the governments 
share of interest on bonds sold to help pay for the bailout over 
30 years costs including interest are estimated at 285 billion 
157 billion of which will come from tax revenues 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
within four months sampl owners must have 150 in tangible 
capital for each 100 in loans by 1995 the standard will be 3 
the provision is aimed at discouraging risky investments by the 
thrift owners in addition many of the accounting loopholes that 
allowed sampl owners to avoid capital requirements have been closed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
both sampls and commercial banks will pay more for the government 
deposit insurance that protects savers accounts up to 100000 
bank premiums will jump from 8 cents per 100 to 15 cents sampl 
premiums will rise from 208 cents to 23 cents 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the bill pushes sampls back into home mortgage lending and out of 
risky investments such as speculative commercial real estate 
projects and junk bonds thrift institutions will be required to 
raise the level of housing and housingrelated loans in their 
portfolios to 70 percent from the current 60 percent sampls now 
involved in risky ventures will have five years to phase out these 
investments 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the lead sampl regulatory agency the federal home loan bank 
board will be dismantled its regulatory divisions will be 
transferred to a new treasury department agency the fund insuring 
sampl deposits moves to the federal deposit insurance corp which 
already insures commercial banks 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the resolution trust corp will be created to sell more than 
300 billion in real estate now owned by bankrupt sampls the fdic 
will do the work overseen by a board headed by the treasury 
secretary the government will be required to give housing 
authorities and nonprofit agencies first chance to buy housing 
from the sampls 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the justice department is getting 75 million a year for the 
next three years to uncover and prosecute fraud at sampls and banks 
it is directed to establish a fraud task force in texas which has 
the biggest concentraton of problem sampls maximum fines for 
financial institution fraud will rise from 5000 a day to 1 
million the maximum jail term from five years to 20 years 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
