<TEXT>
the government on wednesday appealed 
to east germans hoping to obtain exit visas to stop occupying west 
german embassies in eastern europe 
as many as 400 east germans were reported to be holed up in west 
germanys embassies in budapest and prague and at the permanent 
mission in east berlin 
the problem compelled bonn to close its mission in east berlin 
on tuesday 
chancellor helmut kohls chief of staff rudolf seiters said 
relations between east germany and west germany have been improving 
in the past year and that the refugee situation is creating more 
problems than it is solving 
a resolution of the problem has been complicated by the absence 
of many senior west german officials who are on vacation and by 
east germanys refusal to give exit visas to those occupying the 
embassies 
seiters pressed the west german view that east germans wanting 
to emigrate should seek legal means of leaving the country to avoid 
damaging relations between the nations 
he said the number of exit visas granted during the first six 
months of this year 46434 exceeds the number allowed to 
emigrate in all of 1988 
seiters also said the number of east germans granted visas for 
visits to west germany had increased by more than 9 percent this 
year 
but he said west german officials recognized that the desire 
to leave will decrease only when democratic advancements and 
reforms are in place in east germany and he said no immediate 
efforts in that direction were visible 
the west german appeal was issued after a special meeting of 
kohls cabinet early wednesday only five of the 19 federal 
ministers were present many senior bonn officials including kohl 
take their vacations in august 
due to the lack of a quorum the cabinet meeting was limited to 
advisory action 
intergerman affairs minister dorothee wilms has been criticized 
by west german newspapers for failing to return to bonn to deal 
with the refugee problem her spokesman said wednesday she was 
ending her vacation early and was heading back to the capital 
east germans began occupying the west german embassies nearly 
two weeks ago apparently out of frustration over the outlook for 
emigrating through official channels 
the east germans who numbered 131 at the east berlin mission 
when officials closed the premises have said they will not leave 
until they are promised exit visas for west germany 
seiters said the east berlin mission would be reopened only when 
the federal government could ensure normal operations 
the mission has functioned in place of a west german embassy 
since diplomatic relations were established between the two german 
states in 1974 
seiters said those at the closed east berlin mission would be 
allowed to stay until they decide voluntarily to leave 
mission spokesman eberhard grashoff said that as of midday 
wednesday none had left 
