communciation is severed with the mother ship coffey goes solo and 
decides to arm one of the subs nuclear warheads terminate the 
aliens and kill deepcores crew 
before his ultimate demise coffey manages to arm one of 
deepcores mini sea rovers called little geek with a nuclear 
warhead aimed straight into the trough at the alien nation 
the first twothirds of the abyss amount to a fairly good 
adventurethriller with lots of sparkling hip dialogue good 
character development and nonstop action the last third is a joke 
brigman decides to don a dive suit and go into the trough to 
follow little geek he uses a special experimental navy liquid mix 
as his breathing aparatus why does he go because its a dirty 
little job and somebody has to do it he says with a straight 
face this and other cliches pop up with astonishing frequency as 
the abyss begins its plunge into movie camp 
there are odd moments lindsey drowning in freezing water and 
then being revived by bud slapping her face and calling her names 
after adrenalin and shocks have failed a syrupy and trite lindsey 
confessing to all sorts of mistreatment to bud as he almost loses 
conciousness at depths no human has ever gone 
there are pure ripoffs an alien finger resembling little ets 
spindly appendage reaching out and touching a human much the same 
way as in et the extraterrestrial and michaelangelos 
ceiling in the sistine chapel 
but harris and mastrantonio are a good blend and the deepcore 
crew is an interesting lot thanks in part to howard feuers 
casting still its a formula group a strong woman who helps 
leads the crew from disaster a black a burly football type a 
comic who travels with his pet mouse a laidback guy named jammer 
who comes through when the going gets real rough 
mikael salomons photography is superb and the original music 
by alan silvestri has just the right taste of suspense and promise 
but in the end the abyss promises so much and delivers so 
little 
produced by gale anne hurd the abyss is rated pg13 for 
language and thrills 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
motion picture association of america rating definitions 
g general audiences all ages admitted 
pg parental guidance suggested some material may not be 
suitable for children 
pg13 special parental guidance strongly suggested for 
children under 13 some material may be inappropriate for young 
children 
r restricted under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult 
guardian 
x no one under 17 admitted some states may have higher age 
restrictions 
