<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has barred an army 
reserve sergeant from reenlisting because she is a lesbian saying 
sexual orientation is important for maintaining discipline and the 
integrity of command 
the 7th us circuit court of appeals reversed a lower court 
decision allowing miriam benshalom of milwaukee to rejoin the 
army reserve the army had refused to allow her to reenlist 
because of her professed homosexuality 
patrick berigan ms benshaloms attorney said she will 
appeal its our intent to keep up with the appeals and go as far 
as we can he said from his home in milwaukee 
tuesdays ruling reversed a january decision by us district 
judge myron gordon in milwaukee gordon said ms benshaloms first 
amendment rights to freedom of speech were violated by an army 
regulation barring homosexuals 
ruling on the armys appeal the threejudge appeals court panel 
found that while ms benshaloms declaration of homosexuality is 
speech it is also an acknowledgement of identification in a group 
it is the identity that makes her ineligible for military 
service not the speaking of it aloud judge harlington wood jr 
wrote in the decision thus if the armys regulation affects 
speech it does so only incidentally in the course of pursuing 
other legitimate goals 
the appellate court agreed with the armys argument that it 
needs to distinguish military personnel on the basis of sexual 
orientation to maintain discipline and preserve the integrity of 
rank and command 
the court also found that ms benshaloms 5th amendment right 
to equal protection under the law had not been violated 
ms benshalom was traveling in michigan and could not be 
reached for comment said a friend hope gentle contacted at ms 
benshaloms home in milwaukee 
john hoyle the justice department attorney who argued the case 
before the appellate court for the army declined to comment 
ms benshalom 40 was discharged from the army reserve in 1976 
after she said she was a lesbian after a series of court actions 
she was reinstated in september 1987 
ms benshalom applied to reenlist for a sixyear army reserve 
term last august gordon ordered the army to consider her 
reenlistment without regard to her homosexuality 
the army refused to let her rejoin but after gordon found the 
service in contempt of court in january ms benshalom was allowed 
to reenlist the action was however made conditional on the 
outcome of the armys appeal to the circuit court 
