<TEXT>
a chemical companys chief executive 
entered a guilty plea for his company wednesday before a federal 
judge who demanded to see the top man before allowing it to 
plead guilty to polluting a waterway 
us district judge jack tanner told edwin e tuttle pennwalt 
corps chief executive and chairman that he wanted to send a 
message that companies and the people who run them must be 
accountable when they damage the environment 
when natural resources are gone they are gone tanner said 
im one of those judges who wants to get someones attention 
from someone who can do something about it thats why youre 
here 
tuttle who calmly and politely answered tanners questions 
apologized for the accident and said his company has spent millions 
of dollars to improve environmental protection and safety at its 
tacoma plant since the january 1985 spill he said he was confident 
the accident would not be repeated 
pennwalt a philadelphiabased chemical company is merging with 
the french petrochemical company elf aquitaine tanner said while 
there was no way the court could monitor pennwalt or elfs future 
performance he believed tuttle was sincere in promising the 
company would do better 
i assure you it will tuttle replied 
environmentalists and legal experts have said that by requiring 
tuttle to appear in person tanner could set a precedent for 
punishing corporate negligence 
david marshall prosecutor in the case said he thought tanners 
actions would serve as a strong deterrent 
im sure mr tuttle is not experienced in standing up before a 
federal judge marshall said for him to have to come here and 
answer the judges questions im sure it got his attention 
pennwalt was charged after a tank spilled at least 75000 
gallons of bleach into tacomas hylebos waterway which empties 
into puget sound the bleach sodium dichromate contained 
hexavalent chromium which can cause cancer when inhaled in a dry 
form 
in court wednesday pennwalt attorney tom kelly said there was 
a negligent failure to test the tank for structural integrity he 
said pennwalt has since moved its caustic chemical tanks away from 
the waterway and surrounded them with a dike 
in may pennwalt agreed to plead guilty to five misdemeanor 
counts after criminal charges against four company officials 
including three executives were dropped tuttle was not charged 
the company also agreed to pay a 500000 fine and to create a 
600000 trust fund to pay for environmental improvements in the 
tacoma area 
the plea agreement covered two counts of negligently failing to 
maintain adequate storage tanks two of discharging pollutants and 
one of failing to promptly report the spill to the coast guard 
twice however tanner refused to accept guilty pleas from 
attorneys and lower ranking executives of pennwalt demanding 
instead that the top man appear before him 
marshall has said the case is among the first in which the 
government based its prosecution on corporate negligence rather 
than deliberate wrongdoing 
it may also be the first instance in which a corporate executive 
has been ordered to plead the guilt of the corporation said david 
skover professor of civil procedure and constitutional law at the 
university of puget sound law school 
after the hearing tuttle declined to speculate on whether 
leaders of other companies might find themselves in a similar 
situation 
the decision to come out here was not dictated by legal 
considerations tuttle said we just thought that this was the 
best way to bring this situation in tacoma to a satisfactory 
conclusion how other companies or other ceos are going to react i 
really have no way of knowing 
tanner repeatedly asked tuttle who would be accountable for the 
spill and for preventing a recurrence 
im here to tell you that as chief executive officer of 
pennwalt that im here to represent pennwalt and say that pennwalt 
is responsible tuttle said 
