<TEXT>
lyon frances secondlargest city 
won the right wednesday to be the host for the 1990 world chess 
championship final 
delegates to the international chess federations annual 
conference were to have voted on bids submitted by lyon and 
wellington the capital of new zealand but john poole president 
of the new zealand chess federation announced he was withdrawing 
the bid 
poole acted after being called to the conference stage for a 
private discussion with the president of the international chess 
federation florencio campomanes of the philippines 
he said campomanes suggested he withdraw new zealands bid he 
was implying very strongly withdrawal with grace or be thrown 
out poole said in an interview 
earlier david anderton of england a member of the federations 
executive council questioned a stipulation by new zealand that its 
bid was conditional on the participation of world champion garri 
kasparov 
the 26yearold soviet has said privately he might not defend 
his title in a match organized solely by the international chess 
federation known by its french acronym fide 
on tuesday conference delegates voted to deny players any say 
in the choice of venue for the chess final and gave fide the power 
to replace a player who refused to accept match conditions 
the rule changes grew out of a power struggle between fide the 
games governing body and the grandmasters association the 
players organization headed by kasparov who is its president 
gillian houser of the wellington organizing committee accused 
fide officials of political manipulation in choosing the venue 
of the chess final a 24game match scheduled for 10 weeks 
starting oct 7 1990 
i am extremely disappointed in the manner the bids were 
handled by fide she said we arrived in puerto rico and the 
rules were changed 
anderton had also complained that the new zealand bid was not 
accompanied by a bankers draft ms houser said however that the 
bid was underwritten by the new zealand government 
boris spassky a former soviet world champion who now plays for 
france and represented the lyon bid said that while he was pleased 
lyon would be the host he did not think any venue should be forced 
on the players 
the chairman of the grandmasters association bessel kok of 
belgium had urged delegates to show more respect for the wishes of 
grandmasters and head off a possible rift 
canadian delegate nathan divinsky said failure to solicit the 
players opinions on match conditions was like organizing a large 
wedding without consulting the bride and groom 
lyon offered 183 million in prize money plus a winners 
trophy encrusted with diamonds and gold and valued at about 93000 
wellington also offered a prize fund of 183 million plus 
about 370000 for the chess federations fund to promote the game 
in developing countries 
a bitter feud flared between campomanes and kasparov in moscow 
in 1985 when campomanes halted kasparovs first title duel with 
anatoly karpov without result but leaving karpov the champion 
although trailing kasparov had just won two games in a row 
while karpov had failed to secure a victory for 21 games 
kasparov repeatedly charged that campomanes intervened to save 
karpov a charge campomanes denies 
