explorers crossing antarctica with dog sleds 
spent the past two days trying to salvage two of their three sleds 
which were damaged when they crashed in a descent on ice a 
spokeswoman said wednesday night 
the international team led by minnesotan will steger tore down 
both damaged sleds and reconstructed them into one fullsized sled 
and a halfsized sled said expedition spokeswoman cathy demoll 
we were careening down some steep blue ice the two komatek 
homestead sleds crashed together and rolled splitting the runners 
lengthwise steger said in a fax received wednesday at the 
expeditions headquarters in st paul 
it was a big mistake he said we should have been using 
ropes 
blue ice is hard smooth ice that has been blown clear of snow 
demoll said the accident occurred in an area with very low 
visibility and the second sled couldnt slow down on the incline 
none of the six team members was injured nor were any of the 
dogs 
the team had been crossing its first piece of land the jason 
peninsula rather than the flatter smoother ice shelf and have 
encountered what steger called a minefield of crevasses many of 
them deep very deep 
the 36 dogs which normally run 12 to a sled will likely be 
resdistributed along with the teams load as the group continues 
its 4000mile journey demoll said 
stegers group ruled out the expense of sending in a spare sled 
by plane and instead hopes to make it until the scheduled resupply 
mission on aug 25 
steger and fellow international transantarctica expedition 
members from france great britain the soviet union japan and 
china since last month have been making a firstever attempt to 
cross antarctica from west to east the sevenmonth journey is 
designed in part to draw world attention to antarcticas fragile 
environmental and political climate 
