<TEXT>
the federal government has dropped a lawsuit 
accusing northrop of falsifying tests on mx missile guidance 
devices and has agreed not to refile it the aerospace company said 
wednesday 
federal prosecutors could not immediately be reached to explain 
why they dropped the 3 million suit it had alleged fraud and 
violations of the false claims act saying tests on about 20 heat 
exchangers for the mx were never properly conducted 
a lawyer for northrop whistleblowers characterized the suit 
as just a tiny piece of a mosaic of multimilliondollar civil and 
criminal cases filed by former and present northrop employees and 
the government 
unfortunately for northrop our cases are alive and well and 
moving through both the civil and criminal courts attorney 
herbert hafif said 
the company has denied the accusations of overcharges and 
falsifying tests which involve the cruise missile and stealth 
bomber as well as the mx missile 
northrop spokesman tony cantafio said the heat exchanger suit 
filed in federal court here in august 1987 was dismissed with 
prejudice by us district judge david kenyon last week meaning 
it cannot be refiled 
the governments action in dismissing the case with prejudice 
clearly establishes that none of these violations occurred a 
company statement said 
heat exchangers remove heat generated by a guidance system 
component known as the inertial measurement unit a 
basketballsized device that guides nuclear missiles to their 
targets 
the case arose when a heat exchanger component and a test stand 
exploded during testing in january 1986 as part of the dismissal 
of the case northrop agreed to pay the government 45045 for the 
damage to government equipment 
cantafio declined to describe what led up to the dismissal of 
the suit which the company announced late in the day the us 
attorneys office in los angeles referred calls to the justice 
departments special civil litigation section in washington which 
had closed for the day 
hafif the lead attorney for several northrop employees who have 
sued northop under the false claims act characterized the case as 
relatively insignificant 
northrop is a hell of a lot better at issuing press releases 
than it is at building missiles hafif said that press release 
is designed to deceive the public and congress into believing that 
a small government case somehow affects our major cases and 
charges 
the false claims act allows workers or executives who sue their 
employers for fraud against the government to recover as much as 30 
percent of any damages awarded 
the federal government has the option of joining such suits but 
so far has not done so in an mx missile case hafif filed on behalf 
of several plaintiffs led by david peterson a former northrop 
employee 
the case accuses northrop of overcharging falsifying tests and 
using faulty parts on the guidance system for the mx missile and 
hafif said damages could run more than 100 million 
the government has joined another of hafifs civil suits a 30 
million case involving allegations of faked tests on the guidance 
system for the cruise missile 
a federal grand jury has issued a related criminal indictment 
accusing northrop and five employees of fraud and conspiracy for 
allegedly falsifying tests on nucleararmed cruise missiles and for 
supplying equipment that the government knew failed to meet 
specifications 
another hafif lawsuit involves allegations that northrop cost 
taxpayers hundreds of millions of dollars in overcharges and false 
tests on the stealth bomber the government has so far declined to 
join that case 
