<TEXT>
although most were reared in roman catholicism 
hispanics in growing numbers are switching to evangelical churches 
pleasing those congregations but worrying catholic leaders 
both seek to meet special needs of spanishdescended americans 
swelled by a modern tide of immigration they now number nearly 
20 million in this country most of them catholics but studies 
indicate a heavy defection rate to protestant churches of 
evangelical style 
the movement of us hispanics to evangelical protestantism is 
a historic event of great significance says the rev allan 
figueroa deck a catholic specialist on hispanic ministry 
protestantism is achieving a foothold in the hispanic world a 
massive presence that it has never enjoyed before 
evidence of such evangelical inroads into catholicism has turned 
up in many latin american countries as well as in the united states 
deck of the jesuit school of theology at berkeley calif says 
the success of the evangelicals is directly related to the heat 
the passion with which its adherents communicate their message 
hispanics generally like that he writes in the national 
catholic weekly america but its not the style of the typical 
orderly reasoned us catholic service generally shunning 
emotionalism 
surveys by the chicagobased national opinion research center 
indicate a steady increase during the last decade in the proportion 
of us hispanics who are protestants now amounting to 23 percent 
that is up from 16 percent in the l970s in those years 77 
percent listed themselves as catholic and 7 percent other or no 
religion but the l98286 figures indicate only 71 percent remain 
catholic 
the rev andrew greeley catholic sociologist novelist and a 
senior associate at the research center calculates hispanic shifts 
from catholicism to protestantism at 60000 a year nearly a 
million over the last 15 years 
the protestant segment of americans of hispanic origin is not 
only large it is growing rapidly he writes in america 
he notes that the defection rate is lower among 
mexicanamericans 15 percent than among puerto ricans 24 
percent and others 26 percent and lower in the west than in the 
east 
storefront evangelical churches attracting hispanics have 
proliferated in major cities in the east and also on the west coast 
more than threefourths of the spanishorigin protestants are 
either baptists or fundamentalists greeley says 
hispanics have joined fervent protestant groups in which their 
religion provides them with intense activity and community 
support he says adding that catholicism apparently fails to 
meet those emotional communal needs 
the same point is emphasized by deck president of the academy 
of catholic hispanic theologians in the united states 
he says the fundamental problem for catholicism is the 
inflexibility of the parish whose operations are often out 
of gear with the dispositions and needs of hispanics 
the sense of being at home achieving an environment that is 
welcoming and familiar is extremely hard to attain in the large 
urban ethnically mixed parish he says 
us catholicism is very uncomfortable with the cultural core 
of hispanic catholicsm popular religiosity it views all of that 
as at best quaint and at worst superstitious 
enthusiastic religion and affective approaches are downplayed 
our liturgies are orderly and even elegant our preaching 
calmly reasoned and conversational rhetoric and even eloquence are 
shunned 
he says the evangelical protestant appeal to hispanics stresses 
factors of personalism and community small hospitable 
congregations and ministers from the hispanic community 
to accomplish those characteristics he suggests reviving the 
socalled national or ethnic parishes popular in past periods of 
other catholic immigrants now integrated into society their 
special parishes outmoded 
however he says a new wave of immigrants indicates reviving 
such special arrangements to meet the need of hispanics for a 
sense of acceptance their own turf and ministers adapted to 
their language and customs 
such adaptations are applied in evangelical denominations such 
as southern baptists it has 2300 hispanic pastors and a total of 
2612 hispanic congregations up 40 percent in this decade 
catholicism although more than three times bigger has fewer 
hispanic priests estimated under 2000 
united methodists are working to extend a national plan for 
hispanic ministry developed in 1986 
catholic bishops at their june meeting in south orange nj 
took steps for implementing a plan for special efforts among 
hispanics to cope with evangelical proselytism 
a catholic bishop criticized some of that proselytism as 
deceptive this was disputed by a southern baptist leader who said 
hispanics simply were being offered the ggospel message of hope 
