<TEXT>
terence davies has been to america a few times 
now but the english director hasnt stopped looking for gene kelly 
to appear whenever the clouds roll in 
the first film i saw was singing in the rain explained 
the 44yearold director what an introduction i thought life 
was like that when im in america i still think that everybody 
goes to high school everybody has a car everybodys rich 
everybody has wraparound teeth and everyone sings and dances so 
spontaneously 
hollywood musicals provided davies a native of liverpool 
england with the perfect escape from his own unhappy life the 
youngest of 10 children his father was a violent man who 
terrorized the family he died when terence was 7 over the years 
his older siblings filled in details of their fathers behavior 
davies never forgot 
when i was growing i would get up and look at the house and 
go into the street and say i must remember how it looks today i 
dont know why but ive got a very accurate visual and aural 
memory i can remember conversations verbatim he said 
distant voices still lives his new film represents just a 
fraction of those memories davies recreates his childhood by 
showing the pain of a working class family in liverpool in the 
1940s and 50s their hardship increased by a violent father 
but like singing in the rain or meet me in st louis 
another favorite of davies the characters of distant lives are 
sustained by music at any time someone is likely to break into 
song maybe byebye blackbird or roll out the barrel 
pastoral symphony and hymn to the virgin are heard in 
the film too 
the family would go to this pub and a few friends would be 
over and everyone would have a singsong davies said theyd 
go back to the house and have another singsong everyone did it 
i remember my sister was going to buy 10 cents a dance from 
love me or leave me starring doris day and james cagney i was 
agog for weeks on end we were going to have doris day singing in 
our house 
davies new film shows how popular entertainment mixes with real 
life and how the lines get blurred he recalled the bright smiles 
and lilting melodies of hollywood musicals enhancing the dim 
environment of his own city 
when you came out of the cinema into the slums you didnt 
think oh how were terribly deprived it transformed the way you 
looked at your life you thought isnt it fabulous wasnt doris 
day fabulous in that number you were on a high for three or four 
weeks 
my sisters went all the time i was absolutely thrilled with 
meet me in st louis they lived on kensington avenue and we 
lived on kensington street i was sure we were exactly alike i was 
just sorry we didnt have leon ames as a father 
he first wanted to act appearing in amateur productions of 
uncle vanya the cherry orchard and many other plays in 
1972 he went to coventry drama and stumbled upon a chance to 
direct 
i had written a screenplay children which was the first 
part of the autobiographical trilogy that i made over a period of 
10 years no one would do it 
but there was a series on televison called cinema now and 
it told how i could apply to the british film institute for money 
i sent a script in and a year later was asked to go to london where 
i was told to direct 
life and fantasy again blurred davies a complete novice at 
directing was terrified on the set and remembered bitterly the 
crews disrespectful treatment still he fell in love with 
filmmaking 
i realized when i looked down the camera the first time that 
this is what i wanted to do even if i do it badly youve captured 
a moment and there was magic between the filming of it and it 
actually taking place its still terribly exciting 
by 1983 with the completion of madonna and child and 
death and transfiguration the second and third parts of his 
trilogy davies had learned his craft 
each shot for distant voices was planned before the start of 
filming and he quickly cast pete postlethwaite and freda dowie as 
his parents davies only concern was how his siblings would react 
to seeing their lives on screen 
their feelings were mixed he said its opening up a lot 
of suffering but theyre also very proud im a film director and i 
go to america and have lunch at malibu calif i thought it was a 
homage to them i didnt feel it was dirty laundry they suffered 
so much i thought it had to be told 
still davies is disappointed that directing has taken the magic 
out of his own moviegoing experience reality has finally intruded 
on fantasy 
as soon as you create something youve lost your innocence i 
miss going to the cinema and being absolutely transported by it 
now im too critical 
