<TEXT>
once hailed as the showpiece of 
president corazon aquinos government the land reform program is 
so bogged down in corruption and red tape and crippled by loopholes 
that even the official responsible for it wants to change it 
mrs aquino signed the comprehensive agrarian reform law in 
june 1988 to redistribute land to nearly 4 million peasants and 
free rural filipinos from what she called their ancient poverty 
land reform was widely hailed as essential to defeat the 
20yearold communist insurgency in the countryside and break the 
grip on power enjoyed by powerful landlords 
last year the government distributed 150000 land titles 
covering some 254000 acres most of the titles were awarded to 
rice and corn farmers making the effort merely an extension of the 
land reform program decreed by ousted president ferdinand e marcos 
marcos program covered only corn and riceproducing lands but 
the aquino plan encompasses all crop holdings 
critics claim the new law is so flawed that it stands little 
chance of achieving its goals and of being more successful than the 
dozen previous attempts at land reform since the 1930s 
under the program expected to cost 10 billion the government 
will pay landlords for their land those who then take possession 
must repay the government over 30 years at 6 percent annual 
interest 
militant farmer groups claim few can afford to repay and have 
proposed that peasants pay half a sack of rice per hectare 247 
acres a year for three decades 
most critics also cite loopholes favoring landlords landowners 
can retain five hectares 123 acres plus three hectares 74 
acres for each direct heir over age 15 
the department of agrarian reform acknowledges that it is 
uncertain how much of the 24 million acres of agricultural land has 
effectively been removed from the program by exemptions 
under the program estates of more than 50 hectares 1235 
acres are to remain untouched until 1992 the program also gives 
landowners the option of establishing profitsharing plans for 
workers in lieu of transferring titles 
among those who opted for this alternative was mrs aquinos 
family the cojuangcos who established a stock plan for workers on 
their 12350acre sugarcane estate in central luzon 
a review committee suspended the implementation of the profit 
sharing scheme after critics claimed mrs aquinos family grossly 
undervalued their property 
if land reform means to set the peasant free from the 
political and economic domination of the landlord which is the 
essence of a genuine agricultural reform program then on the 
whole it failed to break land monopoly said jaime tadeo leader 
of the leftist philippines peasant movement what it gave were 
just crumbs a few leftovers 
in an attempt to get more large estates for redistribution 
before 1992 the government offered landlords the option of selling 
their property now 
but in several cases the government paid far more for the land 
than it was found to be worth triggering allegations of corruption 
the most controversial case involved the proposed purchase of 
4666 acres in camarines sur province for the peso equivalent of 
29 million the sale was blocked when investigators found the 
land was worth only about 143000 
those scandals have given more ammunition to those attacking 
the program said rep edsel lagman chairman of the house of 
