<TEXT>
a funny thing happened to the ford ranger on its way to becoming 
americas compact pickup truck leader it went from being a work 
truck to being a personal vehicle 
the change was more than just semantics it went below the sheet 
metal 
ford increased the rangers horsepower jazzed up the outside 
with twotone paint and made the interior more carlike as the 
ranger evolved over the decade and its sales rose to more than 
300000 a year 
todays 1989 ford ranger reaps the benefits of all the changes 
with the automaker projecting at the close of the 1989 model year 
that the ranger will retain its title as the topselling compact 
pickup 
the test vehicle was a 1989 ranger xlt twowheeldrive the most 
popular ranger model because it offers a number of optional 
features in one lowpriced package 
the xlt had such amenities as power steering deluxe twotone 
paint a rear window that slides open and amfm stereo cassette 
player with clock price out the door was 10464 
the test truck felt sturdy like a truck and easily 
maneuverable like a car 
its high profile offered a good view of traffic ahead and its 
cloth bench seats with center armrest and easytoread instrument 
panel made for a comfortable interior 
i did feel the jostling shuddering of a trucklike suspension 
over big bumps but it wasnt overly bothersome there also was 
trucklike road noise 
the allterrain tires and rear antilock brakes gave surefooted 
confidence the fivespeed manual transmission was a bit notchy in 
its feel but it and the newfor89 fourcylinder engine with eight 
spark plugs performed admirably 
ford boosted the horsepower 10 percent this model year to 100 
with the 23iter twin plug engine design that uses two spark 
plugs per cylinder 
it helped give the ranger a more peppy ride and more power for 
trailer towing fuel economy was commendable with the epa rating 
at 23 mpg in the city and 27 mpg on the highway 
i wouldnt advise trying to seat three across in the ranger xlt 
regular cab the middle person would either have the gear shifter 
between the legs or would have to sit sideways with the legs 
dangling over to the other passengers area 
this year ford added a columnmounted automatic transmission 
shift lever to help solve this problem if you get the manual 
transmission and carry only two people in the regular cab as i did 
the legroom seems decent and seating is adequate 
ford also offers a super cab that has the largest rear seating 
package in the compact pickup truck segment 
length of the test ranger pickup box was 763 inches bringing 
total vehicle length to 1756 inches while thats considerably 
shorter than the more than 194 inches of overall length of the ford 
f150 fullsize pickups its still sufficient room for hauling 
wood furniture and the lawn mower if the occasion arises 
men between 30 and 35 years of age are 85 percent of the ranger 
buyers and they use the little pickup mostly for personal use such 
as driving to work according to beryl stajich ford division 
compact truck marketing plans manager sixtyfive percent are 
married but most do not have children 
many ranger buyers are firsttime truck buyers he said adding 
that twothirds either trade in cars as they buy the ranger or had 
a car as an alternative purchase he called them middle of the 
roaders who are educated with somewhat upscale contemporary 
lifestyles but are more entrylevel in their purchases 
theyre looking for a good deal a low purchase price 
stajich said and they can customize the ranger it has 
high flexibility 
he noted that when the ranger first came out in 1981 ford saw 
the truck as something that would offer value to more traditional 
truck buyers older married men who would want to get better fuel 
economy from their trucks 
that was true for the first year stajich said then 
toyota led the way adding youthful appeal to their trucks in 
1987 we revamped our marketing and made the ranger sportier 
base price of 9001 for the test ranger is not the lowest among 
compact pickup trucks a similar chevrolet s10 for example starts 
below 9000 
but stajich said many of the features offered in the xlt package 
are separate options on other small pickups such as those offered 
by toyota and nissan and thus could add up to a more expensive 
final price 
consumer reports magazine rates the ford ranger twowheeldrive 
with fourylinder engine as average in its reports of trouble from 
owners of 198387 models 
