a group of retired general motors corp workers 
have sued the automaker saying gm reneged on healthcare coverage 
promises 
the group filed a classaction lawsuit tuesday in federal court 
in los angeles on behalf of more than 80000 salaried retirees 
most of whom live in michigan florida california and ohio 
the suit said the company last year eliminated or reduced some 
coverage for the retirees including chiropractic and psychiatric 
care and imposed copayments and deductibles on basic health 
coverage 
the suit seeks restoration of benefits and compensation for 
those who paid the deductibles and copayments 
gm spokeswoman patricia malloy said the company had no comment 
on the suit because it had not had time to study it 
gm said we would have these benefits for our lifetimes said 
leonard moeller of fenton mich i felt we had a moral and legal 
contract 
they cant take it away now said moeller an accountant who 
retired in 1982 
malloy said all salaried gm workers should have known that their 
health care benefits could change she said last years changes 
were made to encourage active and retired employees to switch to 
more economical health care plans such as health maintenance 
organizations 
currently gm salaried workers have to pay the first 200 of 
medical costs annually and 20 percent of other costs with a 500 
ceiling thus a worker could spend up to 700 a year for health 
care the family limit is 750 a year 
we are all on fixed incomes and we are all at a state in our 
lives when we truly need all of the health benefits that gm 
promised us during our working years moeller said 
moeller said the suit was filed in los angeles because a retiree 
group is active there and that gm may have too much influence if 
the case was filed in michigan 
