<TEXT>
dart drug stores inc faced with high 
debt payments and costs of extensive store renovations has filed 
for protection from creditors under the federal bankruptcy code 
company chairman sheldon fantle said the board of directors 
concluded the company could not continue to make payments on its 
debt much of which was incurred by prior owners who bought the 
chain from founder herbert haft in 1984 for 160 million 
our board determined that it was far better to take this step 
now while our company has substantial resources to implement a 
plan of reorganization 
this makes a lot of sense said kenneth m gassman jr an 
analyst with wheat first securities inc of richmond 
emotionally it was hard for them to make that decision but over 
the long term the company will emerge much stronger because it 
allows them to renegotiate its longterm debt 
fantle led a group of investors that took over management of the 
company in november 1987 at that time dart owed more than 164 
million to bondholders and to its bank lenders it has paid more 
than 26 million in principal and interest payments on that debt 
dart operates 69 retail drug stores in washington dc 
maryland and virginia and five totalplus discount stores in the 
richmond area dart has more than 2000 employees and had sales of 
about 170 million in the fiscal year ended in 1989 
its loss in the third quarter ended april 29 narrowed to 73 
million from 96 million last year revenue in the first nine 
months fell 26 percent to 1288 million from 1749 million a 
year ago 
haft founded dart drug stores in 1954 he sold the company to a 
management group in 1984 before going on to make a series of 
unsuccessful corporate takeover attempts under the mantle of his 
dart group corp which is unrelated to the drugstore chain 
fantle attempted to revamp the company by remodeling stores 
placing new emphasis on customer service a financial restructuring 
and an unusual plan to donate 5 percent of the companys gross 
receipts to charity 
the company filed a petition in us bankruptcy court in 
rockville md placing dart and its subsidiaries under the 
protection of the bankruptcy court while the company prepares a 
plan of reorganization 
under the provisions of chapter 11 the current management will 
continue operating dart drug stores under the supervision of the 
bankruptcy court while the daytoday operations will be up to 
management major actions such as borrowing money would be subject 
to approval of the court 
in several motions tuesday to the bankruptcy court dart sought 
to arrange up to 30 million in new financing from the mellon bank 
of pittsburgh pa those funds would allow the business to pay its 
existing secured creditors and provide a revolving line of credit 
for working capital 
the company also said employees will be paid this friday 
dart also wants to obtain approval to continue making payments 
to charities under its good neighbor fund program 
