<TEXT>
united airlines has found a small crack in 
a fourth boeing 727100 jetliner since the federal aviation 
administration ordered an industrywide inspection in july 
the faa reported tuesday that to date cracks have been found in 
the metallic skins of four united 727s and one american airlines 
727 the cracks ranged in size from 20 inches to less than half an 
inch 
chicagobased united the nations secondlargest airline 
previously reported finding cracks in three planes 
the faa is considering whether to order continuing inspections 
of the 31 oldest 727s registered in the united states said agency 
spokesman david duff the inspections might also be broadened to 
include somewhat newer 727100s as well he said 
the cracks first discovered on united jets occur on the seam 
that joins the upper and lower parts of the fuselage boeing co 
modified the way the seam was joined after building the first 46 
727s increasing the thickness of the splice by inserting a spacer 
piece of metal between the overlapping fuselage sections 
we had never seen cracking along the lower rivet row at the 
splice duff said this was something new 
though the cracks safety implication is not fully understood 
the faa issued an emergency directive ordering airlines to inspect 
the aging 727s for the fuselage cracks and not to fly the planes 
until they were inspected and any cracks repaired 
the united and american planes have been repaired and are back 
in service 
each of the planes had accumulated 46000 to 49000 flights 
boeing had billed the planes as having a design life cycle of 20 
years and 60000 flights said tom cole a boeing spokesman 
boeing still believes the planes can fly indefinitely with 
proper maintenance cole said 
