hoylake investments ltd has released details of 
its cashless offer for bat industries plc but bat again advised 
shareholders not to accept the offer valued at some 216 billion 
in a new twist in hoylakes pursuit of the big british 
conglomerate former us treasury secretary william e simon 
emerged as an investor in the proposed deal and may be interested 
in buying bats farmers group inc insurance division according to 
a report published today 
hoylake said it values its stockanddebt offer for bat at the 
equivalent of 1414 a share but the stock closed at 1365 a 
share tuesday on londons stock exchange up 5 cents 
the filing of an offer document is a normal step in british 
takeover procedures the offer must now stay open at least 21 days 
hoylake consisting of anglofrench financier sir james 
goldsmith british merchant banker jacob rothschild australian 
investor kerry packer and other investors said tuesday the group 
wouldnt specify how it might make the debt package behind their 
takeover offer more marketable until after the bids standing with 
us regulators is clear 
for every 100 ordinary bat shares hoylake would pay hoylake 
variableinteres senior secured notes valued at 684 subordinated 
hoylake notes valued at 41820 and 274 worth of hoylake 
exchangeable loan stock convertible into 387 shares of anglo group 
plc a goldsmith company 
later bat issued a statement from the louisville ky 
headquarters of its us subsidiary batus inc reiterating its 
rejection of the proposed buyout and advising stockholders not to 
sell their shares 
bat which is the worlds biggest tobacco company said its 
international concentration on growth businesses had paid off with 
a 38 percent compound return to shareholders since 1980 and there 
was continued potential for rapid earnings growth 
bat chairman patrick sheehy stated that the hoylake offer 
ignored those prospects and consisted of securities of dubious 
value 
the scheme is principally designed to enrich messrs 
goldsmith rothschild and packer at the expense of bat industries 
shareholders sheehy stated 
some of bats institutional investors have attacked the bids 
lack of cash and of any assurance that the debt offered in exchange 
for bat shares would be tradable 
goldsmith said the group couldnt speculate on how and when all 
the details of the debt package would come to light but said 
bankers trust international and drexel burnham lambert inc 
wouldnt have lent their names to such an effort if the 
securities couldnt be made liquid 
the wall street journal reported that the unexpected 
intervention of simon in the proposed acquisition of bat which 
would be europes biggest takeover could lend credibility to the 
takeover attempt led by goldsmith 
simon told the journal that you have to consider bill simon an 
interested player in any goldsmith sale of farmers which bat 
acquired late last year for 52 billion 
goldsmith has indicated that if he prevails in his quest for bat 
he would retain the companys tobacco business and sell its retail 
paper and financial services divisions besides farmers bats us 
operations include the retail chains saks fifth avenue and marshall 
field 
in an interview with the newspaper simon described his interest 
in farmers as preliminary and he said there werent any firm plans 
for a sale of farmers by hoylake 
the bid for bat is being reviewed by us insurance regulators 
the hoylake investors intend to explore whether it makes a 
difference to us regulators whether it is simon who ends up 
acquiring farmers said simon who has become a pioneer of 
leveraged buyouts since leaving government service 
bat has been lobbying the british government to investigate the 
proposed takeover on the grounds that the highly leveraged 
financing was against the public interest 
