<TEXT>
michael norris is in search of the 
perfectly cooked chicken but his tools are more likely to include 
a slide rule than a spatula 
norris a 26yearold graduate chemical engineering student at 
the university of louisville is trying to create a mathematical 
model for showing how quickly chicken pieces will cook under 
varying conditions 
financed by a 15000 grant from kentucky fried chicken norris 
is attempting to develop the model for his masters thesis at the 
equipment performance lab of the companys col sanders technical 
center 
basically all cooking is a physical phenomenon said dr 
mohan rao a senior research scientist for kentucky fried chicken 
the nations biggest fried chicken chain with norris model we 
should be able to tell exactly what the process should be he 
said 
whenever the company changes its brand of shortening or uses a 
new type of pressure cooker it has to alter the cooking procedure 
the company would use the formula being developed by norris to 
replace trial and error testing methods 
minor improvements in productivity translate into a 
significant amount of money says richard m detwiler a 
spokesman at kentucky fried chicken which sells nearly 6 billion 
worth of chicken and other foods annually 
using an overhead projector norris creates graph outlines of 
drumsticks measured in two positions to arrive at an average 
dimension then with what norris says is best explained as 
fouriers law he uses the measurements to work out an equation 
that will predict how quickly various parts of the chicken will 
cook 
fouriers law states that with two masses the greater the 
temperature difference the faster the heat transfers rao said 
the 40yearold rao spent 15 years as a professor of food 
processing at the university of georgia in athens last month he 
was named an adjunct professor at the university where he will 
teach a class on food processing next spring 
norris said he had no particular interest in working with 
chicken before he was selected for the project however standing 
in a room surrounded by trays of fried chicken norris said he 
might consider a career in foodprocess control 
